2. Path selection: framing the research intent (important)

Before selecting a task or models, the research was framed using two high-level research paths, based on intent, not technique.

Path A — Problem-driven research (application-first)

Starts from a specific real-world problem

Models are selected as tools to solve that problem

Architecture reasoning is required but subordinate to the application

Insights are often problem- and domain-specific

Path B — Field-driven / phenomenon-driven research (Understanding-first)

Starts from a field or task as a testbed

The goal is to study model behavior, properties, limitations, and trade-offs

The task is not the contribution; it is the vehicle for analysis

Results are generalizable across applications

Real-world relevance appears as implications, not claims

This work explicitly follows Path B.

3. Research hierarchy used to structure the topic

Under Path B, the topic was structured using the following hierarchy:

Path B: Field-driven research
 └── Chosen field / task (what is being studied)
      └── Research lenses (how it is studied)


Key clarifications:

Semantic segmentation, object detection, classification, etc. are tasks / fields

Architecture comparison, robustness, generalisation, efficiency are research lenses

Lenses are not fields and are not paths

Multiple lenses can coexist under the same Path B study

A valid Path B paper is therefore:

One field / task + one main research lens + (optionally) one or more supporting lenses

