7. Meaning of “architecture comparison” in this context

Architecture comparison is not library-level benchmarking.
It refers to comparing architectural design philosophies, such as:

Encoder–decoder structure

Strength and role of skip connections

Multi-scale context aggregation

Lightweight vs heavyweight encoders

In this study:

Architecture = independent variable

Robustness behavior = dependent variable

8. Meaning of “robustness” in this work

Robustness is defined as:

Performance stability when inputs deviate from ideal, clean training conditions.

This explicitly excludes adversarial robustness.

Realistic degradations considered (scope-controlled)

Gaussian noise (sensor noise)

Blur (motion or defocus)

Resolution downscaling (distance, compression)

Critical experimental constraint:

All models are trained only on clean data

Robustness is evaluated only at inference

No retraining or adaptation is performed

This isolates inherent architectural robustness, consistent with Path B goals.

9. Model architectures selected (with rationale)

A small, conceptually diverse set of CNN-based architectures was chosen.
Each represents a distinct inductive bias.

Model 1: U-Net with ResNet encoder

Strong encoder–decoder structure

Explicit skip connections

Emphasis on spatial detail preservation

Represents: boundary-aware architectures

Model 2: DeepLabV3+ with ResNet backbone

Atrous (dilated) convolutions

Multi-scale context aggregation

Emphasis on semantic consistency

Represents: context-heavy architectures

Model 3 (optional): U-Net with MobileNet encoder

Lightweight encoder

Lower capacity, higher efficiency

Represents: efficiency-biased architectures

The comparison is conceptual and architectural, not merely performance-based.

